Edinburgh Footfall Analysis¶

Here's a short notebook that serves as a small guide on how to do some basic data analysis with Python (using pandas, matplotlib, scikit-learn and a bit of numpy) on a real dataset I came across online.

Part 1 - Fetching Data¶

First thing we want to do is get the data.

We can either manually download it from: http://www.edinburghopendata.info/dataset/monthly-footfall-data, or (once we know the direct links to the data) we can have Python automatically download it so when someone goes to recreate this analysis they don't have to go searching.

In [1]:
#direct links to data

urls = ['http://www.edinburghopendata.info/dataset/41586704-092d-4afe-b634-4fb7ea20fedd/resource/9762f4b7-ba25-40f2-a707-94d45956d916/download/footfall2012.zip',
        'http://www.edinburghopendata.info/dataset/41586704-092d-4afe-b634-4fb7ea20fedd/resource/993bb312-3bb3-4c41-b1ba-8239adeb16ac/download/footfall2013.zip',
        'http://www.edinburghopendata.info/dataset/41586704-092d-4afe-b634-4fb7ea20fedd/resource/ba2e9ae6-0c84-457d-8d6c-6ff303ed244f/download/footfall2014.zip']

#urllib.requests for handing URLs, urlretrieve to download from a URL

from urllib.request import urlretrieve

#i'm using a list comprehension to make it look nice, basically just downloading each of the years worth of footfalls 
#by calling 'urlretrieve' on the url, saving it into the 'data' folder with the filename being the .zip name
#get the .zip name by splitting the url into "chunks" separated by '/' and getting the final chunk

[urlretrieve(url, 'data/%s' % url.split('/')[-1]) for url in urls];

Now we have the zip files downloaded, we want to extract each one to get the .csv files containing the actual data.

In [2]:
import os, zipfile

#get a list with each element being the name of the file

files = os.listdir('data/')

#for each file, convert into ZipFile object and then perform extractall on it

[zipfile.ZipFile('data/%s' % file).extractall('data/') for file in files if file.endswith('.zip')];

All .csv files have the same headers. A few issues though:

  • the data from 2012 is only from March onwards
  • the data for "Shandwick Pl: Lothian Buses" doesn't appear until May 2012
  • the data for "Grassmarket: Grassmarket Hotel" and "High Street: Bella Italia" don't appear until May 2013
  • the data for "High Street: Bella Italia" stops appearing after May 2014 (potentially was only collected for that one year)

To make things a bit easier to analyse, we'll ignore data for the last three locations.

In [4]:
#get all the csv files, ignoring the zip files

all_csv_files = [file for file in os.listdir('data/') if file.endswith('.csv')]

#concatenate them together into one big dataframe
#we use the thousands=',' to tell pandas this data is an integer using a comma to separate the thousands from the hundreds

data = pd.concat((pd.read_csv('data/%s' % file, thousands=',') for file in all_csv_files))

print(data.shape)

When we used thousands=',' when reading the .csv files pandas automatically infered the types for most of the columns, however it left 'Date' as an 'object' & we want it to be a 'datetime'. To sort this out, we'll just convert it using to_datetime.

data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'], format='%d/%m/%Y') #need to state how the dates are formatted

Part 3 - Visualizing Data¶

Now we can finally plot the data using matplotlib. We'll plot it as a line and as a scatterplot.

%matplotlin inline allows for plotting matplotlib graphs without the .show() method.

Note: by default pandas doesn't let you scatterplot using datetime axis, but if you change the style of a line plot you basically get a scatterplot.

In [10]:
%matplotlib inline 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=1, figsize=(20,20)) #this is how you plot mutiple axes on the same figure

data.plot(x='Date', ax=ax[0]); #ax=ax[0] states this plot should be on axis 0, the top

data.plot(x='Date', style='x', ax=ax[1]);

Something weird is going on between August 2012 and May 2013. It looks like the data for Leith Walk and Princes Street has got mixed up!

I've checked online and asked around for any closures around Princes Street during this time, and couldn't find anything.

However, we're going to persist (for now) and instead of analysing each location individually just analyse the total footfall.

Let's add a Total column to our data and then re-plot it.

In [11]:
data['Total'] = data.sum(axis=1) #add a new axis that is the sum of the other axes

Part 3 - Tabulating Data¶

Let's use some pivot tables to see if we can get anything from the data.

First, let's see if we see any trends in the days of the week.

In [16]:
import numpy as np

#we set the index (the 0th column) to be the date converted into the 'dayofweek'
#dayofweek: 0 = monday, 1 = tuesday, etc.
#aggfunc creates a column with each function applied

pivot_days = pd.pivot_table(data, index=data['Date'].dt.dayofweek, values='Total', aggfunc=[np.mean, np.std, np.max, np.min])

Part 4 - Clustering Data¶

Finally, we're going to use principal component analysis (PCA) and Gaussian mixture models to automatically find clusters in the data.

Let's get the average footfall for each of the 7 locations (not the total) for every day of the year.

In [25]:

X = pivot

X.shape
Out[26]:
(1036, 7)

Now let's use PCA to reduce the dimensionality from 7 to 2 so we can plot it.

In [27]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

X2 = PCA(2).fit_transform(X) #PCA into 2 dimensions, fit_transform both fits the model and applies the dimensionality reduction

X2.shape
Out[27]:
(1036, 2)
In [28]:
plt.scatter(X2[:,0], X2[:,1]);

The clusters look pretty distinct!

Now we'll use a Gaussian mixture model to automatically cluster the data.

In [29]:
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture

gmm = GaussianMixture(2) #state the number of clusters
gmm.fit(X) #fit to our data
labels = gmm.predict(X) #get a list with the label for each data point in X
In [30]:
plt.scatter(X2[:,0], X2[:,1], c=labels);
plt.colorbar();

Now let's plot the data for each label to see if we can figure out what the distinct clusters are.

In [31]:
pivot[labels==1].plot(style='*', legend=False);
In [32]:
pivot[labels==0].plot(style='*', legend=False);

Let's put them on comparable axes using sharex = True so things are a little easier to see.

In [33]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=1, sharex=True, figsize=(10,10)) #sharex = True means we want both subplots to share the same x-axis

pivot[labels==1].plot(style='*', legend=False, ax=ax[0]);

pivot[labels==0].plot(style='*', legend=False, ax=ax[1]);

So what are these clusters?
